That's amazing.

261
00:08:32,211 --> 00:08:33,910
- You even do "Sergeant Keroro?" - "Sergeant Keroro?"

262
00:08:33,911 --> 00:08:36,850
- Dororo. - "I'm Sergeant Dororo."

263
00:08:36,851 --> 00:08:38,350
(Dororo in "Sergeant Keroro")

264
00:08:38,351 --> 00:08:40,091
"I failed once again."

265
00:08:40,291 --> 00:08:41,450
(Happy)

266
00:08:41,451 --> 00:08:42,520
- How impressive. - For real.

267
00:08:42,521 --> 00:08:43,990
- Finally. - It's here.

268
00:08:43,991 --> 00:08:45,830
- DiCaprio. - VoiceCaprio.

269
00:08:45,831 --> 00:08:48,131
- VoiceCaprio? - Let's listen with our eyes closed.

270
00:08:48,331 --> 00:08:49,460
Close your eyes.

271
00:08:49,461 --> 00:08:50,501
(Please close your eyes.)

272
00:08:50,861 --> 00:08:52,031
"Do you trust me?"

273
00:08:52,801 --> 00:08:55,701
"Here. Put your feet up."

274
00:08:55,801 --> 00:08:57,041
"Open your arms."

275
00:08:57,341 --> 00:08:59,841
"Now open your eyes."

276
00:09:00,911 --> 00:09:02,410
(Making a sound effect)

277
00:09:02,411 --> 00:09:03,581
- That startled me. - And the music plays.

278
00:09:04,511 --> 00:09:06,980
I opened my eyes, and DiCaprio is gone.

279
00:09:06,981 --> 00:09:08,510
Where is he? Where did he go?

280
00:09:08,511 --> 00:09:10,181
- He took a flight overseas. - Did he?

281
00:09:10,281 --> 00:09:11,881
Oh, no. He has left.

282
00:09:12,091 --> 00:09:15,821
Soo Jin. The majority of your works are animations.

283
00:09:15,921 --> 00:09:17,420
My work was mainly animations.

284
00:09:17,421 --> 00:09:21,591
Title-wise, I did about 200 of them.

285
00:09:22,031 --> 00:09:25,130
Episode-wise, I must've done about 5,000 to 6,000.

286
00:09:25,131 --> 00:09:27,731
Out of all of them, you must have a favorite character.

287
00:09:27,901 --> 00:09:29,040
It could be an animation.

288
00:09:29,041 --> 00:09:33,311
I do adore many characters from movies and animations.

289
00:09:33,541 --> 00:09:36,311
But if I were to choose my top favorite,

290
00:09:36,811 --> 00:09:38,440
it would be Inuyasha.

291
00:09:38,441 --> 00:09:41,611
I love both the storyline and the character the most.

292
00:09:41,911 --> 00:09:43,421
What about Hanamichi Sakuragi?

293
00:09:43,551 --> 00:09:44,920
- Hanamichi Sakuragi. - You also did the movie.

294
00:09:44,921 --> 00:09:46,620
True. He's in my top three...

295
00:09:46,621 --> 00:09:48,350
- favorite characters. - I see. Hanamichi Sakuragi.

296
00:09:48,351 --> 00:09:51,621
But both Hanamichi Sakuragi's appearance and voice...

297
00:09:51,821 --> 00:09:53,961
are completely different from mine.

298
00:09:54,291 --> 00:09:55,561
We're totally different.

299
00:09:55,861 --> 00:09:59,170
I had to make up a voice for Hanamichi Sakuragi.

300
00:09:59,171 --> 00:10:00,570
It gave me some trouble.

301
00:10:00,571 --> 00:10:03,300
- So he made one up. - When I first recorded "Slam Dunk,"

302
00:10:03,301 --> 00:10:05,171
- we used videotapes. - In the past.

303
00:10:05,471 --> 00:10:08,710
Back then, the recording environment was far from adequate.

304
00:10:08,711 --> 00:10:12,110
In a small booth during midsummer,

305
00:10:12,111 --> 00:10:14,750
- ACs were off due to the sound. - five to six men were inside.

306
00:10:14,751 --> 00:10:16,920
- Really? - We recorded without AC...

307
00:10:16,921 --> 00:10:19,350
for about 4 to 5 hours while sweating buckets.

308
00:10:19,351 --> 00:10:20,751
- The recordings were tough. - The environment.

309
00:10:21,191 --> 00:10:22,761
But I still remember going all out...

310
00:10:23,061 --> 00:10:25,090
because the animation was so fun.

311
00:10:25,091 --> 00:10:27,930
- "The First Slam Dunk," - The movie.

312
00:10:27,931 --> 00:10:31,231
an animated movie, was released after 26 years.

313
00:10:31,761 --> 00:10:33,770
I auditioned for it and got the role again.

314
00:10:33,771 --> 00:10:35,000
You took the audition?

315
00:10:35,001 --> 00:10:37,770
You took the audition and weren't automatically cast?

316
00:10:37,771 --> 00:10:41,611
But you were in charge of that character for so long.

317
00:10:41,841 --> 00:10:43,340
The production crew...

318
00:10:43,341 --> 00:10:44,840
- should've asked you to voice it, - The thing is...

319
00:10:44,841 --> 00:10:45,910
not hold an audition.

320
00:10:45,911 --> 00:10:49,050
Even all the Japanese voice actors in the movie...

321
00:10:49,051 --> 00:10:51,051
released two years ago changed.

322
00:10:51,151 --> 00:10:53,150
Every single voice actor was changed.

323
00:10:53,151 --> 00:10:55,460
Despite voicing the character in the past,

324
00:10:55,461 --> 00:10:57,590
I was asked to take the audition.

325
00:10:57,591 --> 00:10:59,230
- And you took it? - I took the audition.

326
00:10:59,231 --> 00:11:01,261
And you were able to voice Hanamichi Sakuragi again?

327
00:11:01,391 --> 00:11:02,601
Correct.

328
00:11:03,031 --> 00:11:04,130
How amazing.

329
00:11:04,131 --> 00:11:07,100
Stamina is one thing, but keeping the same vocalization must be hard.

330
00:11:07,101 --> 00:11:08,200
- Exactly, the voice. - Right.

331
00:11:08,201 --> 00:11:10,300
Although I recorded Hanamichi Sakuragi...

332
00:11:10,301 --> 00:11:13,171
of "Slam Dunk" after 26 years,

333
00:11:13,371 --> 00:11:16,140
there were animations I've been voicing...

334
00:11:16,141 --> 00:11:18,911
- for over 30 years. - Of course.

335
00:11:19,181 --> 00:11:22,521
For example, Jimmy Kudo of "Detective Conan..."

336
00:11:22,621 --> 00:11:26,390
and Luffy of "One Piece." I've been voicing them for 27 years.

337
00:11:26,391 --> 00:11:27,620
(Maintaining the voices for years)

338
00:11:27,621 --> 00:11:29,020
And ever since the animations started.

339
00:11:29,021 --> 00:11:31,190
Let me tell you this in advance.

340
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:33,191
The works dubbed in Korea...

341
00:11:33,331 --> 00:11:35,090
aren't confirmed...

342
00:11:35,091 --> 00:11:36,860
- by the Korean production staff. - Right.

343
00:11:36,861 --> 00:11:39,930
If it's by Japan, Japan gives the confirmation.

344
00:11:39,931 --> 00:11:42,940
If it's by Spielberg, he needs to give the confirmation.

345
00:11:42,941 --> 00:11:44,101
- Really? - For real?

346
00:11:44,301 --> 00:11:46,010
- That's amusing. - We don't...

347
00:11:46,011 --> 00:11:48,141
confirm anything on our side.

348
00:11:48,311 --> 00:11:50,511
The voice video is sent to the original author's country...

349
00:11:50,641 --> 00:11:53,111
and gets confirmed by their production crew.

350
00:11:53,751 --> 00:11:55,380
That's why it's not easy.

351
00:11:55,381 --> 00:11:57,621
- I... - Soo Jin voiced DiCaprio.

352
00:11:57,721 --> 00:12:00,921
Did Director James Cameron confirm it last?

353
00:12:01,021 --> 00:12:03,020
- I guess so. - Fortunately, when recording...

354
00:12:03,021 --> 00:12:05,020
Director James Cameron's "Titanic,"

355
00:12:05,021 --> 00:12:07,331
we didn't have such a system.

356
00:12:07,531 --> 00:12:09,930
- Is it fortunate? - Yes, it's fortunate.

357
00:12:09,931 --> 00:12:12,571
KBS cast me, and I voiced the role.

358
00:12:12,771 --> 00:12:14,030
- These days... - But...

359
00:12:14,031 --> 00:12:17,400
But as my dubs of DiCaprio received good reviews,

360
00:12:17,401 --> 00:12:19,271
- I continued to dub him. - Right.

361
00:12:19,411 --> 00:12:22,911
DiCaprio's recent works, like "Don't Look Up..."

362
00:12:23,241 --> 00:12:26,081
and "Once Upon a Time in Hollywood,"

363
00:12:26,551 --> 00:12:28,850
were confirmed by the original production crew.

364
00:12:28,851 --> 00:12:32,820
Not all the characters you've dubbed must've received good reviews.

365
00:12:32,821 --> 00:12:34,650
- No. - What received bad reviews?

366
00:12:34,651 --> 00:12:36,360
The first work I received bad reviews for...

367
00:12:36,361 --> 00:12:38,460
and caused an uproar was Luffy of "One Piece."

368
00:12:38,461 --> 00:12:40,390
- Really? - But your voice suits him well.

369
00:12:40,391 --> 00:12:42,091
The original Japanese voice actor...

370
00:12:42,601 --> 00:12:45,101
for Luffy of "One Piece" is a woman.

371
00:12:45,971 --> 00:12:47,500
- There's a unique voice actress... - Right.

372
00:12:47,501 --> 00:12:51,100
who can make such a hot-blooded young man's voice.

373
00:12:51,101 --> 00:12:53,740
She's a globally renowned voice actress.

374
00:12:53,741 --> 00:12:56,581
I couldn't dub Luffy with the same tone as hers.

375
00:12:57,111 --> 00:13:00,750
So I reinterpreted the character and made a voice more suitable for me.

376
00:13:00,751 --> 00:13:01,910
- It must've been tricky. - Those who liked...

377
00:13:01,911 --> 00:13:03,081
the original voice...

378
00:13:03,351 --> 00:13:05,480
- didn't like it. - I can imagine.

379
00:13:05,481 --> 00:13:07,220
- But people like it now. - But those fans...

380
00:13:07,221 --> 00:13:08,920
got used to your voice...

381
00:13:08,921 --> 00:13:10,260
- and liked it later, right? - Yes.

382
00:13:10,261 --> 00:13:11,460
He became my version of Luffy.

383
00:13:11,461 --> 00:13:14,331
Children who watched it while growing up love it.

384
00:13:14,461 --> 00:13:17,630
- Next is Sun. - Me.

385
00:13:17,631 --> 00:13:20,830
Sun wrote, "A wide-ranging voice actress."

386
00:13:20,831 --> 00:13:23,401
Is it because you voice a wide range of works?

387
00:13:23,501 --> 00:13:27,971
It means I can voice a wide range of characters,

388
00:13:28,341 --> 00:13:30,310
from a cute animal...

389
00:13:30,311 --> 00:13:31,810
to different women.

390
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:35,011
As I can successfully make all sorts of voices,

391
00:13:35,151 --> 00:13:37,781
that's what my fans call me.

392
00:13:38,021 --> 00:13:39,450
- Would you like to hear it? - Yes, please.

393
00:13:39,451 --> 00:13:40,520
Snippets of them.

394
00:13:40,521 --> 00:13:42,360
- Pororo. - Pororo.

395
00:13:42,361 --> 00:13:44,560
"Hi, Men on a Mission guys!"

396
00:13:44,561 --> 00:13:46,131
"It's me, Pororo."

397
00:13:47,161 --> 00:13:49,060
"It's nice to meet you all."

398
00:13:49,061 --> 00:13:50,531
(Laughing)

399
00:13:51,031 --> 00:13:52,630
That's unbelievable.

400
00:13:52,631 --> 00:13:54,430
- You voiced that too? Psyduck? - She mentioned earlier.

401
00:13:54,431 --> 00:13:55,640
- "Duck." - Psyduck?

402
00:13:55,641 --> 00:13:57,270
(Psyduck of "Pokemon")

403
00:13:57,271 --> 00:14:00,010
- "Duck." - Right, that's all...

404
00:14:00,011 --> 00:14:02,280
- "Duck." - the character says.

405
00:14:02,281 --> 00:14:03,540
"Duck."

406
00:14:03,541 --> 00:14:05,280
- That's it? - It's Ddochi.

407
00:14:05,281 --> 00:14:06,480
Ddochi?

408
00:14:06,481 --> 00:14:08,681
"My goodness, what's this?"

409
00:14:09,021 --> 00:14:12,021
"You all look exactly like the ones I saw at home on TV."

410
00:14:12,121 --> 00:14:13,620
"I'm so happy to see you."

411
00:14:13,621 --> 00:14:15,150
"Nice to meet you, brothers."

412
00:14:15,151 --> 00:14:16,560
That's just Ddochi.

413
00:14:16,561 --> 00:14:17,990
(Summoning old characters)

414
00:14:17,991 --> 00:14:19,090
- Jessie. - It's Jessie.

415
00:14:19,091 --> 00:14:20,991
"If you ask who I am,"

416
00:14:21,091 --> 00:14:23,260
"it's mannerly to answer."

417
00:14:23,261 --> 00:14:26,970
"To conquer Men on a Mission, my name is Jessie."

418
00:14:26,971 --> 00:14:29,471
- She flicked her hair like Jessie. - Jessie.

419
00:14:30,401 --> 00:14:31,701
What? Juliet?

420
00:14:33,241 --> 00:14:37,181
"Prince Ho Dong. Why must you be Ho Dong?"

421
00:14:37,781 --> 00:14:39,411
"Please abandon that name."

422
00:14:39,651 --> 00:14:41,751
- And say that you love me. - Gosh.

423
00:14:41,981 --> 00:14:43,281
Isn't that Princess Nak Rang?

424
00:14:43,781 --> 00:14:45,690
(Prince Ho Dong only has Princess Nak Rang.)

425
00:14:45,691 --> 00:14:47,620
- I'm itchy all over. - It's Jolie.

426
00:14:47,621 --> 00:14:48,791
- It's Angelina Jolie. - "Well..."

427
00:14:48,991 --> 00:14:51,291
"Yeong Cheol, I'm impressed."

428
00:14:51,591 --> 00:14:54,231
"You have lips that are as attractive as mine."

429
00:14:55,131 --> 00:14:56,761
- She didn't sound genuine though. - That was good.

430
00:14:57,961 --> 00:14:59,600
Emotional authenticity matters as well in acting.

431
00:14:59,601 --> 00:15:00,800
- She has such a versatile voice. - Impressive.

432
00:15:00,801 --> 00:15:01,930
- But... - She changes her voice so freely.

433
00:15:01,931 --> 00:15:03,601
- Even I find her fascinating. - I immerse myself in my characters.

434
00:15:03,971 --> 00:15:06,340
I never knew that the same person played Pororo and Angelina Jolie.

435
00:15:06,341 --> 00:15:08,270
- My point, exactly. - Her voice changed completely.

436
00:15:08,271 --> 00:15:09,510
- "Pororo the Little Penguin..." - She can speak like a sexy woman...

437
00:15:09,511 --> 00:15:10,710
and a baby.

438
00:15:10,711 --> 00:15:14,410
also airs in foreign countries. When that happens,

439
00:15:14,411 --> 00:15:16,151
- it must be dubbed... - That's right.

440
00:15:16,351 --> 00:15:17,580
- by foreign voice actors. - Oh, that's right.

441
00:15:17,581 --> 00:15:19,890
- I'm the reference in that case. - You're the original voice.

442
00:15:19,891 --> 00:15:20,920
It's the opposite of Soo Jin's case.

443
00:15:20,921 --> 00:15:22,620
- Her voice is the standard. - It's reversed.

444
00:15:22,621 --> 00:15:24,020
- That's right. - They must use it as the reference.

445
00:15:24,021 --> 00:15:26,690
- I've seen some videos online... - Hi. I'm Pororo.

446
00:15:26,691 --> 00:15:28,660
where the footage of the cartoon...

447
00:15:28,661 --> 00:15:31,400
dubbed in different countries was combined.

448
00:15:31,401 --> 00:15:32,470
Such videos are fun to watch.

449
00:15:32,471 --> 00:15:36,901
Voice actors are popular in Korea,

450
00:15:37,001 --> 00:15:38,741
but there are so many other countries...

451
00:15:39,071 --> 00:15:42,910
where voice actors of those countries are very popular.

452
00:15:42,911 --> 00:15:44,110
- Right. - Yes, that's true.

453
00:15:44,111 --> 00:15:45,180
- Some voice actors hold concerts. - That's right.

454
00:15:45,181 --> 00:15:48,880
There are a large number of fans who know all the characters...

455
00:15:48,881 --> 00:15:51,480
played by their favorite voice actors...

456
00:15:51,481 --> 00:15:53,020
- and chase the voice actors. - Yes. Exactly.

457
00:15:53,021 --> 00:15:55,450
Thus, you may have more foreign fans...

458
00:15:55,451 --> 00:15:59,190
- than Korean fans. - She may be more popular overseas.

459
00:15:59,191 --> 00:16:00,360
It makes sense since she played Pororo.

460
00:16:00,361 --> 00:16:02,330
- Jang Hoon knows much unexpectedly. - Indeed.

461
00:16:02,331 --> 00:16:03,500
He watched "Pororo the Little Penguin" all the time...

462
00:16:03,501 --> 00:16:04,700
when he was a basketball player.

463
00:16:04,701 --> 00:16:07,071
- Don't be ridiculous. - Judging by what I've heard...

464
00:16:07,171 --> 00:16:09,941
- I was 40 when the cartoon started. - What's unexpected is...

465
00:16:10,201 --> 00:16:14,011
- Well... She dubbed Pororo, right? - Yes.

466
00:16:14,111 --> 00:16:17,580
I think she gets calls from her acquaintances very often.

467
00:16:17,581 --> 00:16:18,710
- That's right. - Oh, those with babies...

468
00:16:18,711 --> 00:16:20,610
If their kids don't behave...

469
00:16:20,611 --> 00:16:22,010
- or refuse to eat... - They let the kids talk to Pororo?

470
00:16:22,011 --> 00:16:24,020
They personally know her, right? So they could ask her a favor.

471
00:16:24,021 --> 00:16:25,320
- Exactly. - I was asked such favors...

472
00:16:25,321 --> 00:16:26,621
- so many times. - Me too.

473
00:16:26,851 --> 00:16:29,490
Since my acquaintances' kids grew up a lot,

474
00:16:29,491 --> 00:16:30,960
they don't ask me that favor anymore.

475
00:16:30,961 --> 00:16:32,360
But when their kids were younger...

476
00:16:32,361 --> 00:16:34,090
- Right. - I had been dubbing Pororo...

477
00:16:34,091 --> 00:16:35,391
- since they started watching it. - That's right.

478
00:16:35,931 --> 00:16:37,860
- I mean, really... - When we were...

479
00:16:37,861 --> 00:16:40,700
having tea together after work,

480
00:16:40,701 --> 00:16:42,231
she would answer a call and say,

481
00:16:42,471 --> 00:16:45,441
"Listen. You should not eat chocolate."

482
00:16:45,911 --> 00:16:48,541
After that, we continued chatting.

483
00:16:48,671 --> 00:16:50,740
- She does it whenever she's asked. - "What are you scheduled for next?"

484
00:16:50,741 --> 00:16:52,210
She would say, "Hang on a second."

485
00:16:52,211 --> 00:16:55,351
"About that, you should listen to your mommy."

486
00:16:55,751 --> 00:16:58,751
- She got such calls nonstop. - Exactly.

487
00:16:59,151 --> 00:17:01,391
You can watch "Pororo the Little Penguin,"

488
00:17:01,691 --> 00:17:05,021
but you should chew your food well.

489
00:17:05,321 --> 00:17:07,090
- Promise me. - I promise.

490
00:17:07,091 --> 00:17:08,630
It's a promise.

491
00:17:08,631 --> 00:17:11,001
You always keep your promises, right?

492
00:17:11,031 --> 00:17:12,360
When kids don't listen to you,

493
00:17:12,361 --> 00:17:13,770
one call could solve the problem.

494
00:17:13,771 --> 00:17:14,830
- So I heard. - Yes.

495
00:17:14,831 --> 00:17:17,470
It's true. Here's a true story. My friend's baby...

496
00:17:17,471 --> 00:17:20,170
was being hospitalized in a pediatric ward.

497
00:17:20,171 --> 00:17:22,510
And there were several other children in the room.

498
00:17:22,511 --> 00:17:24,910
- My friend called me. - I see.

499
00:17:24,911 --> 00:17:26,250
She asked me...

500
00:17:26,251 --> 00:17:28,650
- to say some cheerful words. - That's nice of you.

501
00:17:28,651 --> 00:17:30,550
So I did as she asked,

502
00:17:30,551 --> 00:17:32,321
and it turned out that she put me on speaker.

503
00:17:32,591 --> 00:17:34,090
I spoke in Pororo's voice as requested.

504
00:17:34,091 --> 00:17:35,990
I said, "Stay strong. I hope you get well soon."

505
00:17:35,991 --> 00:17:37,990
"Make sure to eat well, okay?"

506
00:17:37,991 --> 00:17:39,591
My friend said to me,

507
00:17:39,791 --> 00:17:41,830
sounding really excited,

508
00:17:41,831 --> 00:17:43,460
"Hey, the kids here are going crazy."

509
00:17:43,461 --> 00:17:47,201
"The kids in the hospital room are screaming and going wild."

510
00:17:47,301 --> 00:17:49,340
- I bet they all got well soon. - It's really incredible.

511
00:17:49,341 --> 00:17:51,541
- Then... Yes. - I spoke to some in real-time.

512
00:17:51,901 --> 00:17:54,110
And I sent a voice message to others as a gift.

513
00:17:54,111 --> 00:17:56,011
Then I upgraded my gift. Now I do something different.

514
00:17:56,181 --> 00:17:58,540
- I buy a Pororo doll. - Yes.

515
00:17:58,541 --> 00:18:00,981
I place the doll in front of a camera...

516
00:18:01,181 --> 00:18:03,851
and record a video by myself at home.

517
00:18:03,951 --> 00:18:06,851
I make the Pororo doll fill the screen...

518
00:18:07,151 --> 00:18:10,161
and I move the doll, hiding behind it.

519
00:18:10,221 --> 00:18:11,790
- Then I record my voice as Pororo. - Before you go to bed,

520
00:18:11,791 --> 00:18:14,061
- I send the video to my friends. - make sure to brush your teeth.

521
00:18:14,091 --> 00:18:15,900
You're so good just like the meaning of your name.

522
00:18:15,901 --> 00:18:17,660
Then can you say a few words to the children viewers?

523
00:18:17,661 --> 00:18:19,970
- We'll put Pororo on the screen. - Please do that.

524
00:18:19,971 --> 00:18:22,331
- Tell them to watch only our show. - No, that's not what I mean.

525
00:18:22,431 --> 00:18:23,700
Tell them to listen to their parents.

526
00:18:23,701 --> 00:18:25,371
- I prepared for it. - Oh, she brought the doll.

527
00:18:26,471 --> 00:18:27,471
Please say a few words.

528
00:18:27,472 --> 00:18:28,940
Actually, Ho Dong,

529
00:18:28,941 --> 00:18:31,681
I prepared to make a video message for Si Hoo.

530
00:18:31,741 --> 00:18:34,510
- I'm sorry, but Si Hoo is... - He's too old for this.

531
00:18:34,511 --> 00:18:37,150
- His body physique is now... - He's too old for this.

532
00:18:37,151 --> 00:18:39,620
half between mine and Ho Dong's.

533
00:18:39,621 --> 00:18:41,951
- He's about 190cm tall... - He's 188cm tall.

534
00:18:42,421 --> 00:18:43,890
- You see, his foot size is... - He's very tall.

535
00:18:43,891 --> 00:18:46,390
Si Hoo's foot size is the same as mine.

536
00:18:46,391 --> 00:18:49,330
The reason why I want to make a video message for Si Hoo is...

537
00:18:49,331 --> 00:18:51,560
that he watched the cartoon when he was little.

538
00:18:51,561 --> 00:18:53,400
- Yes, he really liked the cartoon. - I heard he liked it very much.

539
00:18:53,401 --> 00:18:55,900
- Ho Dong, you said it on TV. - Yes, I did.

540
00:18:55,901 --> 00:18:57,701
- Then say a few words to Si Hoo. - Okay.

541
00:18:57,801 --> 00:18:59,441
(Dear Si Hoo)

542
00:18:59,671 --> 00:19:02,071
Hi, Si Hoo.

543
00:19:02,171 --> 00:19:05,741
This is Pororo. It's nice to see you.

544
00:19:05,911 --> 00:19:08,981
Si Hoo, I have something to tell you.

545
00:19:09,181 --> 00:19:11,120
When you were little,

546
00:19:11,121 --> 00:19:14,190
you adored me very much, right?

547
00:19:14,191 --> 00:19:17,020
- This is touching. - I've become...

548
00:19:17,021 --> 00:19:20,030
an internationally famous star...

549
00:19:20,031 --> 00:19:25,231
because you loved me very much when you were little.

550
00:19:25,331 --> 00:19:28,271
Thank you for loving me, Si Hoo.

551
00:19:28,431 --> 00:19:31,471
And Si Hoo, you play golf these days, right?

552
00:19:31,771 --> 00:19:34,611
I, Pororo, will be...

553
00:19:34,711 --> 00:19:37,940
rooting for you forever.

554
00:19:37,941 --> 00:19:40,480
- Go, Si Hoo! Bye! - Amazing.

555
00:19:40,481 --> 00:19:43,181
- That was so touching. I'm moved. - Nice.

556
00:19:43,981 --> 00:19:45,280
- Ho Dong must be reminded... - You know...

557
00:19:45,281 --> 00:19:46,550
of the days when Si Hoo was little.

558
00:19:46,551 --> 00:19:48,191
- You know... - It was so touching.

559
00:19:48,221 --> 00:19:50,990
If you think about it, Pororo is older than him, isn't he?

560
00:19:50,991 --> 00:19:52,421
- Yes, he is. - He's older than Si Hoo.

561
00:19:52,631 --> 00:19:53,791
His age...

562
00:19:54,191 --> 00:19:56,560
When elementary school students are asked if they know Pororo,

563
00:19:56,561 --> 00:19:58,130
they try to look mature.

564
00:19:58,131 --> 00:19:59,730
They snort, acting like they don't watch it anymore.

565
00:19:59,731 --> 00:20:01,030
- Right. They'd react that way. - That's how they react.

566
00:20:01,031 --> 00:20:03,641
Middle school students react in a positive way. "I know Pororo."

567
00:20:03,841 --> 00:20:05,900
And as for high school students, they say,

568
00:20:05,901 --> 00:20:07,810
"Oh, my! Pororo!" They go wild, apparently.

569
00:20:07,811 --> 00:20:09,781
- They get excited to think of it. - Yes, indeed.

570
00:20:09,911 --> 00:20:11,981
(Oh, yes! Here comes Pororo!)

571
00:20:12,341 --> 00:20:13,681
("I Love To Play All Day" from "Pororo the Little Penguin")

572
00:20:15,281 --> 00:20:17,220
(Everyone sings together, which is surprising.)

573
00:20:17,221 --> 00:20:20,191
(The most enthusiastic reaction)

574
00:20:20,421 --> 00:20:22,690
- I wondered why. - Yes.

575
00:20:22,691 --> 00:20:24,221
And I came to a conclusion.

576
00:20:24,321 --> 00:20:26,661
I think they feel touched and nostalgic...

577
00:20:27,031 --> 00:20:29,260
when they see how the lead character of the cartoon...

578
00:20:29,261 --> 00:20:31,800
that they watched when they were little...

579
00:20:31,801 --> 00:20:35,030
- is still loved by children, - Right.

580
00:20:35,031 --> 00:20:36,740
and that the cartoon is still popular...

581
00:20:36,741 --> 00:20:39,640
- when they've grown up. - Right.

582
00:20:39,641 --> 00:20:42,410
That's why I think Pororo means a lot to them.

583
00:20:42,411 --> 00:20:43,741
(They may feel touched and nostalgic as Pororo is still loved!)

584
00:20:43,941 --> 00:20:46,181
How many years has it been since Pororo was created?

585
00:20:46,281 --> 00:20:48,010
- The cartoon started in 2003. - Oh, I see.

586
00:20:48,011 --> 00:20:50,181
- It started in 2003. - He's supposed to speak like this.

587
00:20:50,351 --> 00:20:51,981
"Hello. I am Pororo."

588
00:20:52,181 --> 00:20:54,890
"I haven't seen you guys in a while."

589
00:20:54,891 --> 00:20:56,090
Pororo is supposed to speak this way.

590
00:20:56,091 --> 00:20:58,160
I've been dubbing this character for about 23 years.

591
00:20:58,161 --> 00:21:00,391
- Pororo shouldn't get older. - His throat must be sore.

592
00:21:00,591 --> 00:21:02,530
- Let's move on to Ji Hwan... - Okay.

593
00:21:02,531 --> 00:21:04,060
- as he played the grown-up Pororo. - He did...

594
00:21:04,061 --> 00:21:05,061
- "SBS Inkigayo..." - "SBS..."

595
00:21:05,062 --> 00:21:06,301
Ji Hwan wrote,

596
00:21:06,901 --> 00:21:08,330
"Mr. Animal Farm."

597
00:21:08,331 --> 00:21:09,841
He's most famous for that show.

598
00:21:10,301 --> 00:21:12,270
Ji Hwan's voice appeared...

599
00:21:12,271 --> 00:21:14,270
- on many variety shows. - That's right.

600
00:21:14,271 --> 00:21:16,510
- Have you not dubbed... - "What do we do?"

601
00:21:16,511 --> 00:21:18,010
- any cartoons at all? - Right. Ji Hwan...

602
00:21:18,011 --> 00:21:20,080
Most people recognize you from "Animal Farm."

603
00:21:20,081 --> 00:21:22,250
It changed around the time when Doh Hyeong debuted.

604
00:21:22,251 --> 00:21:24,320
- We got a job at a radio station. - We started our career that way.

605
00:21:24,321 --> 00:21:26,390
We were cast for a radio drama in the beginning.

606
00:21:26,391 --> 00:21:29,621
- After acting in some radio dramas, - Oh, they do all kinds of work.

607
00:21:29,691 --> 00:21:32,120
building experience for a certain period of time...

608
00:21:32,121 --> 00:21:34,860
as an in-house voice actor at a radio station,

609
00:21:34,861 --> 00:21:37,301
then we get cast for a foreign movie or an animation.

610
00:21:37,631 --> 00:21:40,200
Most voice actors start with an animation.

611
00:21:40,201 --> 00:21:42,940
I made my debut in an animation.

612
00:21:42,941 --> 00:21:45,000
- Which one? - It's "Time Travel Tondekeman."

613
00:21:45,001 --> 00:21:46,310
- Maybe you know the animation. - Oh, Tondekeman!

614
00:21:46,311 --> 00:21:47,640
- The one with Tondekeman. - Tondekeman.

615
00:21:47,641 --> 00:21:48,710
(The animation that aired in the 1990s...)

616
00:21:48,711 --> 00:21:49,781
(where they travel to the past and help historical figures)

617
00:21:49,881 --> 00:21:51,780
- I played Prince Dandarn. - Right? What?

618
00:21:51,781 --> 00:21:53,351
- "Princess Shalala!" - Oh, my.

619
00:21:53,651 --> 00:21:55,780
"Abdullah, I won't let you off."

620
00:21:55,781 --> 00:21:57,050
- Oh, wait. - I dubbed Prince Dandarn.

621
00:21:57,051 --> 00:21:59,990
You sound a little bit like Soo Jin.

622
00:21:59,991 --> 00:22:01,590
When we play in an animation, our voices sound similar.

623
00:22:01,591 --> 00:22:02,760
- Come on. - He sounds similar to Soo Jin.

624
00:22:02,761 --> 00:22:04,320
I've done many kinds of work.

625
00:22:04,321 --> 00:22:06,230
- But I've been the narrator... - That was so funny.

626
00:22:06,231 --> 00:22:09,160
of "Animal Farm" for about 26 years.

627
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:10,460
Then let's start with a golden retriever.

628
00:22:10,461 --> 00:22:13,031
I was going to do a character. Why would you show a dog?

629
00:22:14,171 --> 00:22:15,570
They showed a dog.

630
00:22:15,571 --> 00:22:16,800
- They look alike. - I mean...

631
00:22:16,801 --> 00:22:17,870
- "Hey, mister." - Their eyes look similar.

632
00:22:17,871 --> 00:22:20,310
- "Bring me some food, will you?" - Right.

633
00:22:20,311 --> 00:22:22,270
- "Bring me the bone I was chewing." - That's impressive.

634
00:22:22,271 --> 00:22:23,410
What's that?

635
00:22:23,411 --> 00:22:25,340
- "Gosh, those brats." - Oh, my.

636
00:22:25,341 --> 00:22:27,110
"They don't even give me any dog chews."

637
00:22:27,111 --> 00:22:28,710
- "Seriously, I'm so upset." - He sounds so cute.

638
00:22:28,711 --> 00:22:30,020
(He can make a voice of a small dog as well.)

639
00:22:30,021 --> 00:22:31,850
"What? Hey, look over there."

640
00:22:31,851 --> 00:22:33,790
"Hey, the older ones have gathered over there."

641
00:22:33,791 --> 00:22:35,221
- Is that a meerkat? - Yes, it is.

642
00:22:36,121 --> 00:22:38,460
"Finally, the problem is solved. Done!"

643
00:22:38,461 --> 00:22:40,031
- That's what I've been waiting for! - Oh, there's more?

644
00:22:40,561 --> 00:22:42,130
"They lost their lives while chatting away."

645
00:22:42,131 --> 00:22:44,100
"Safety First!"

646
00:22:44,101 --> 00:22:46,131
- That's it. That's the one. - "They died while trying it."

647
00:22:46,571 --> 00:22:49,640
"How did this classroom change?"

648
00:22:49,641 --> 00:22:50,800
Oh, that's from "Love House."

649
00:22:50,801 --> 00:22:51,801
Is there more?

650
00:22:52,671 --> 00:22:55,170
I dubbed Kiminobu Kogure, Akira Sendoh, and the commentator...

651
00:22:55,171 --> 00:22:56,511
of "Slam Dunk," all three of them.

652
00:22:57,011 --> 00:22:58,440
"Sakuragi, you shouldn't do that."

653
00:22:58,441 --> 00:22:59,781
"Hey, I'm Akira Sendoh."

654
00:23:00,051 --> 00:23:01,280
"Right at that moment..."

655
00:23:01,281 --> 00:23:02,510
I dubbed all three of them by myself.

656
00:23:02,511 --> 00:23:04,721
- All three of them? - He played several characters.

657
00:23:04,981 --> 00:23:06,450
- Wait. Johnny Depp? - "Pirates of the Caribbean?"

658
00:23:06,451 --> 00:23:07,690
(Johnny Depp from "Pirates of the Caribbean")

659
00:23:07,691 --> 00:23:09,350
"I am the captain of the Black Pearl."

660
00:23:09,351 --> 00:23:12,290
"I am the pirate of the Caribbean."

661
00:23:12,291 --> 00:23:13,561
"I am Johnny Depp."

662
00:23:14,631 --> 00:23:16,230
- Tom Cruise. - Tom Cruise?

663
00:23:16,231 --> 00:23:17,531
"People call me Mr. Tom..."

664
00:23:17,901 --> 00:23:18,901
Why...

665
00:23:19,261 --> 00:23:20,401
am I embarrassed?

666
00:23:21,801 --> 00:23:23,740
"My missions are always impossible."

667
00:23:23,741 --> 00:23:26,140
Stop it. That's enough. Quit it.

668
00:23:26,141 --> 00:23:28,770
- Oh, my gosh. Brad Pitt? - That's incredible.

669
00:23:28,771 --> 00:23:31,410
"I've always been with Angelina Jolie."

670
00:23:31,411 --> 00:23:32,980
"I am Brad Pitt."

671
00:23:32,981 --> 00:23:34,610
"Hey, DiCaprio, have you been well?"

672
00:23:34,611 --> 00:23:36,081
- "It's been a while." - "It's been a while, indeed."

673
00:23:38,181 --> 00:23:40,190
All the world stars are here.

674
00:23:40,191 --> 00:23:42,250
- They're so good. - So we...

675
00:23:42,251 --> 00:23:44,020
- Oh, you dubbed Brad Pitt. - It's fascinating.

676
00:23:44,021 --> 00:23:47,290
Singers must understand this easily.

677
00:23:47,291 --> 00:23:48,760
- There are different genres. - Yes.

678
00:23:48,761 --> 00:23:49,761
Hip-hop artists...

679
00:23:49,762 --> 00:23:50,930
- Right. - mostly do hip-hop music.

680
00:23:50,931 --> 00:23:52,400
- RnB singers do RnB. - That's right.

681
00:23:52,401 --> 00:23:54,130
- They mostly do RnB music. - Yes.

682
00:23:54,131 --> 00:23:55,500
As for me,

683
00:23:55,501 --> 00:23:57,170
I've done many different genres.

684
00:23:57,171 --> 00:23:58,770
- You have a wide spectrum. - I started my career...

685
00:23:58,771 --> 00:24:00,010
- in an animation, - He has a variety of experiences.

686
00:24:00,011 --> 00:24:01,641
- but I also did "Janghak Quiz." - What?

687
00:24:01,941 --> 00:24:04,141
I read the questions on the show.

688
00:24:04,541 --> 00:24:05,740
The director of the show heard my voice...

689
00:24:05,741 --> 00:24:07,450
and said I had a nice voice.

690
00:24:07,451 --> 00:24:09,250
You know how they reshuffle TV slots on a regular basis.

691
00:24:09,251 --> 00:24:11,520
- Directors are reassigned to shows. - Right.

692
00:24:11,521 --> 00:24:13,350
And some directors recommended me to other directors.

693
00:24:13,351 --> 00:24:15,020
So the number of the shows I worked on increased...

694
00:24:15,021 --> 00:24:16,360
one by one.

695
00:24:16,361 --> 00:24:17,960
I got cast for 20 shows, and then 30 shows.

696
00:24:17,961 --> 00:24:20,160
That's how I got cast for 30 shows as a fixed narrator of the shows.

697
00:24:20,161 --> 00:24:22,131
It was like that back in the day. So...

698
00:24:22,461 --> 00:24:24,060
Although I dubbed movies...

699
00:24:24,061 --> 00:24:26,030
and animations as well,

700
00:24:26,031 --> 00:24:28,370
people recognize me...

701
00:24:28,371 --> 00:24:30,000
- "Animal Farm?" - from variety shows.

702
00:24:30,001 --> 00:24:31,500
- True. - I didn't do "Knee-Drop Guru..."

703
00:24:31,501 --> 00:24:33,470
- for that long. - Really?

704
00:24:33,471 --> 00:24:35,941
That show aired for seven years, I think.

705
00:24:36,341 --> 00:24:37,610
- Isn't that long? - That's a long time.

706
00:24:37,611 --> 00:24:38,611
- That's a really long time. - That's a long time.

707
00:24:38,612 --> 00:24:40,850
- Seven years is not a long time. - How long is long, then?

708
00:24:40,851 --> 00:24:42,780
People call me Mr. Animal Farm.

709
00:24:42,781 --> 00:24:44,180
I've been doing the show for 26 years now.

710
00:24:44,181 --> 00:24:46,220
- So that's considered long. - Yes. I mean...

711
00:24:46,221 --> 00:24:48,390
You call it a long-lasting show when it airs for at least ten years.

712
00:24:48,391 --> 00:24:49,550
- We all have a lot of experience. - That's true.

713
00:24:49,551 --> 00:24:51,091
He has about 40 years of experience.

714
00:24:51,461 --> 00:24:53,190
She has about 35 years of experience.

715
00:24:53,191 --> 00:24:54,991
And I have about 33 years of experience.

716
00:24:55,391 --> 00:24:56,830
We all have so much experience in this field.

717
00:24:56,831 --> 00:24:59,330
No voice actors become successful only in 1 or 2 years.

718
00:24:59,331 --> 00:25:02,100
You're most famous as Mr. Animal Farm.

719
00:25:02,101 --> 00:25:05,270
Many people do say that I'm famous as Mr. Animal Farm.

720
00:25:05,271 --> 00:25:07,410
This happens when I go to a restaurant.

721
00:25:07,411 --> 00:25:09,170
There are some ladies at another table,

722
00:25:09,171 --> 00:25:11,440
and my friend says I'm famous and that they should get my autograph.

723
00:25:11,441 --> 00:25:12,580
- Then they ask who I am. - Right.

724
00:25:12,581 --> 00:25:13,710
My friend says, "He does 'Animal Farm.'"

725
00:25:13,711 --> 00:25:15,010
- Then they go, "Oh, I see." - "Oh, I see."

726
00:25:15,011 --> 00:25:16,011
"So what does he grow?"

727
00:25:17,051 --> 00:25:18,280
- They don't know who I am. - Oh, I see.

728
00:25:18,281 --> 00:25:20,350
- They don't recognize your voice? - No.

729
00:25:20,351 --> 00:25:22,550
- When people see you guys... - They think he runs an animal farm?

730
00:25:22,551 --> 00:25:24,290
- They think you run an animal farm? - Wherever you guys go,

731
00:25:24,291 --> 00:25:25,960
- people recognize your faces. - Yes.

732
00:25:25,961 --> 00:25:27,660
But as for me, no matter how much I talk,

733
00:25:27,661 --> 00:25:28,890
elderly ladies don't recognize my voice.

734
00:25:28,891 --> 00:25:30,831
- Right. It's understandable. - It's not my face they see on TV.

735
00:25:31,231 --> 00:25:34,300
How did you come up with the tone you used for "Knee-Drop Guru?"

736
00:25:34,301 --> 00:25:36,171
I worked a gig job before.

737
00:25:36,541 --> 00:25:38,970
It was an audio-response...

738
00:25:38,971 --> 00:25:40,740
- fortune-telling service. - I see.

739
00:25:40,741 --> 00:25:41,910
You call on this number,

740
00:25:41,911 --> 00:25:44,341
and the recorded voice comes out.

741
00:25:44,711 --> 00:25:45,780
"Here's the result."

742
00:25:45,781 --> 00:25:48,310
"If you go southeast, you'll meet someone helpful for you."

743
00:25:48,311 --> 00:25:49,750
- "Today, you must go to a place..." - That's...

744
00:25:49,751 --> 00:25:50,920
- I recorded such lines. - My goodness.

745
00:25:50,921 --> 00:25:53,890
- Oh, really? - I did it as a gig job.

746
00:25:53,891 --> 00:25:56,790
I remembered how I read the results,

747
00:25:56,791 --> 00:25:58,190
- so I suggested the tone. - He spoke with the same tone.

748
00:25:58,191 --> 00:25:59,730
"What are you worried about?"

749
00:25:59,731 --> 00:26:02,430
"If you go southeast..."

750
00:26:02,431 --> 00:26:04,330
The director liked the tone and told me to go ahead.

751
00:26:04,331 --> 00:26:06,470
"What he's worried about is..."

752
00:26:06,471 --> 00:26:07,670
That's how I came up with the tone.

753
00:26:07,671 --> 00:26:08,930
(That's how the signature tone of the narration was created.)

754
00:26:08,931 --> 00:26:11,970
And there were some lines I mumbled during the show.

755
00:26:11,971 --> 00:26:14,671
One time, Sung Si Kyung came on the show.

756
00:26:14,871 --> 00:26:17,540
"Gosh, he strayed so far from the topic."

757
00:26:17,541 --> 00:26:20,611
I added ad-lib lines like this when the guest went off the topic.

758
00:26:21,051 --> 00:26:23,080
When Sung Si Kyung was on the show, I didn't say anything.

759
00:26:23,081 --> 00:26:25,520
The director asked me to add an ad-lib line.

760
00:26:25,521 --> 00:26:27,290
I said, "Well, I'm not a big fan of Sung Si Kyung."

761
00:26:27,291 --> 00:26:29,220
And they recorded what I said...

762
00:26:29,221 --> 00:26:31,620
- and let it air. - Oh, no. That's bad.

763
00:26:31,621 --> 00:26:34,030
- They let it air? - Ho Dong must remember that.

764
00:26:34,031 --> 00:26:35,530
- They really let it air? - Really?

765
00:26:35,531 --> 00:26:37,760
- That's quite intense. - Right.

766
00:26:37,761 --> 00:26:41,170
- And sometime after that... - The director is bold and daring.

767
00:26:41,171 --> 00:26:43,501
Sometime after that, Sung Si Kyung came back on the show.

768
00:26:44,301 --> 00:26:46,740
I mumbled, "Is he famous enough..."

769
00:26:46,741 --> 00:26:49,611
"to be on this show twice?"

770
00:26:49,881 --> 00:26:51,281
And the director let that air too.

771
00:26:52,011 --> 00:26:54,080
(Those mean staff members)

772
00:26:54,081 --> 00:26:56,720
I feel so apologetic toward Si Kyung...

773
00:26:56,721 --> 00:26:58,951
although I've never met him in person.

774
00:26:59,421 --> 00:27:00,590
So I'd like to take this chance to apologize to him.

775
00:27:00,591 --> 00:27:03,260
Si Kyung, I really didn't mean what I said. It was a joke.

776
00:27:03,261 --> 00:27:04,990
- Of course. - And trust me.

777
00:27:04,991 --> 00:27:07,660
I listen to no other singers' songs than yours.

778
00:27:07,661 --> 00:27:09,661
(I listen to no other singers' songs than yours.)

779
00:27:10,001 --> 00:27:12,630
And I have a close friend whose name is Sung Sik.

780
00:27:12,631 --> 00:27:14,370
- Sung Sik? - Yes, Sung Sik.

781
00:27:14,371 --> 00:27:16,371
- I think it's too late. - I always...

782
00:27:16,601 --> 00:27:17,640
- Sung Si Kyung! - Too many years have passed.

783
00:27:17,641 --> 00:27:19,370
- It's too late to apologize. - Sung Si Kyung!

784
00:27:19,371 --> 00:27:21,611
- Next up is Doh Hyeong. - Jayce.

785
00:27:21,971 --> 00:27:24,080
Doh Hyeong wrote, "Thousand voices."

786
00:27:24,081 --> 00:27:25,640
- He's the youngest of all guests. - "Thousand voices."

787
00:27:25,641 --> 00:27:26,750
- He's the youngest of all. - That's right.

788
00:27:26,751 --> 00:27:28,650
Unlike the other three friends,

789
00:27:28,651 --> 00:27:30,220
I work in many different fields...

790
00:27:30,221 --> 00:27:32,480
including games, animations, YouTube,

791
00:27:32,481 --> 00:27:35,920
various events, narration, and so on.

792
00:27:35,921 --> 00:27:37,420
That's why I described my career like that.

793
00:27:37,421 --> 00:27:38,890
- Show us your most famous work. - I'm curious.

794
00:27:38,891 --> 00:27:40,660
Kyung Hoon and I know this character so well.

795
00:27:40,661 --> 00:27:42,830
- Oh, you dubbed "Fairy Tale" too. - You know this series?

796
00:27:42,831 --> 00:27:45,600
Of course, I know Natsu. I absolutely love this animation.

797
00:27:45,601 --> 00:27:47,530
"Hi, everyone. When you're watching 'Fairy Tale,'"

798
00:27:47,531 --> 00:27:48,970
"stay away from the television."

799
00:27:48,971 --> 00:27:51,071
"Fire dragon's slash!" This is how Natsu speaks.

800
00:27:51,601 --> 00:27:53,040
I always said to stay away from the television.

801
00:27:53,041 --> 00:27:54,210
- And as for this character... - Black Cat.

802
00:27:54,211 --> 00:27:55,470
I've never seen this character in my life.

803
00:27:55,471 --> 00:27:57,480
(Black Cat from "Miraculous")

804
00:27:57,481 --> 00:27:59,280
- This one is popular these days. - It's popular.

805
00:27:59,281 --> 00:28:01,110
"Miracula-culous."

806
00:28:01,111 --> 00:28:03,280
- "Miracula-culous?" - "Miracula-culous?"

807
00:28:03,281 --> 00:28:04,450
He can't even read it.

808
00:28:04,451 --> 00:28:06,650
- "Miracula-culous?" - I mean, "Miraculous."

809
00:28:06,651 --> 00:28:07,790
It's written right there, but he can't read it right.

810
00:28:07,791 --> 00:28:10,220
- He can't even read. - Gosh, seriously.

811
00:28:10,221 --> 00:28:12,290
"Hey, Ho Dong. Did you call me, my lady?"

812
00:28:12,291 --> 00:28:13,430
"Ancient disaster!"

813
00:28:13,431 --> 00:28:15,031
(Black Cat from "Miraculous")

814
00:28:15,231 --> 00:28:16,730
- Oh, that's Sabo. - Sabo from "One Piece."

815
00:28:16,731 --> 00:28:17,731
He dubbed so many characters.

816
00:28:17,761 --> 00:28:19,601
"Luffy is my precious little brother."

817
00:28:20,101 --> 00:28:21,930
"I won't let you off if you harass Luffy."

818
00:28:21,931 --> 00:28:23,140
"Dragon's claws!"

819
00:28:23,141 --> 00:28:24,401
- It's called "dragon's claws." - That's cool.

820
00:28:24,801 --> 00:28:26,070
- Oh, I know this one. - Spider-Man.

821
00:28:26,071 --> 00:28:27,870
Finally, a character that Soo Geun knows came out.

822
00:28:27,871 --> 00:28:29,810
"Hi. I'm your kind neighbor Spider-Man."

823
00:28:29,811 --> 00:28:32,181
"Aunt May will scold me. I should hurry home."

824
00:28:32,881 --> 00:28:34,210
I dubbed this character.

825
00:28:34,211 --> 00:28:36,750
- I know this one so well. - Hee Chul's favorite character.

826
00:28:36,751 --> 00:28:39,150
"I fight for a brighter tomorrow. Hit it with the hammer."

827
00:28:39,151 --> 00:28:40,151
"Power slam!"

828
00:28:40,391 --> 00:28:41,790
- This is how Rakan speaks. - That was Jayce.

829
00:28:41,791 --> 00:28:42,820
Rakan and Xayah are a couple.

830
00:28:42,821 --> 00:28:45,090
"It's time to dance. Xayah!"

831
00:28:45,091 --> 00:28:46,760
"Did I tell you this? I love you."

832
00:28:46,761 --> 00:28:48,661
Right. He's supposed to call for Xayah.

833
00:28:49,031 --> 00:28:50,601
(Impressed)

834
00:28:50,761 --> 00:28:52,661
("Culinary Class Wars")

835
00:28:53,131 --> 00:28:55,030
(Your class will be determined now.)

836
00:28:55,031 --> 00:28:56,431
(What's going on? What is this?)

837
00:28:57,101 --> 00:29:00,871
"Your class will be determined now."

838
00:29:01,741 --> 00:29:04,180
"Culinary Class Wars."

839
00:29:04,181 --> 00:29:06,240
That's the voice I heard a lot on TV.

840
00:29:06,241 --> 00:29:07,610
- I didn't know he did that. - There's a reason he's here.

841
00:29:07,611 --> 00:29:09,780
- Interesting. The Shinbundang Line. - This one will be interesting.

842
00:29:09,781 --> 00:29:12,150
"The Shinbundang Line is coming in."

843
00:29:12,151 --> 00:29:13,151
You expect that tone, right?

844
00:29:13,651 --> 00:29:15,290
- But it's a little different. - How so?

845
00:29:15,291 --> 00:29:16,990
In the Shinbundang Line, the travel time between stops...

846
00:29:16,991 --> 00:29:18,960
is up to 5 to 6 minutes.

847
00:29:18,961 --> 00:29:21,060
So I spoke like a radio DJ.

848
00:29:21,061 --> 00:29:22,230
- How did you speak? - How?

849
00:29:22,231 --> 00:29:23,231
- That's new. - This is how.

850
00:29:23,232 --> 00:29:25,000
"Have a happy day."

851
00:29:25,001 --> 00:29:28,131
"I hope you spend the day with a smile."

852
00:29:28,431 --> 00:29:32,141
"This stop is Yangjae Citizens' Forest."

853
00:29:32,401 --> 00:29:35,040
The announcement for the line number two...

854
00:29:35,041 --> 00:29:36,470
- It's different from what I heard. - It's a little different.

855
00:29:36,471 --> 00:29:38,080
- Did you memorize those lines? - What is the original tone?

856
00:29:38,081 --> 00:29:40,110
"This stop is Men on a Mission."

857
00:29:40,111 --> 00:29:41,750
- Right. That's it. - "Men on a Mission."

858
00:29:41,751 --> 00:29:44,381
- "The door opens..." - "The door opens on the right."

859
00:29:44,851 --> 00:29:46,250
I spoke with a relaxing tone for the Shinbundang Line.

860
00:29:46,251 --> 00:29:47,750
- I see. - So this is how they do these days.

861
00:29:47,751 --> 00:29:48,920
I wanted people to feel like...

862
00:29:48,921 --> 00:29:50,690
they were listening to a neighborhood friend.

863
00:29:50,691 --> 00:29:54,630
When they asked me to record the subway announcements,

864
00:29:54,631 --> 00:29:56,261
they paid me according to the number of stations.

865
00:29:57,201 --> 00:29:58,430
- They did? - Really?

866
00:29:58,431 --> 00:29:59,460
They paid me per station.

867
00:29:59,461 --> 00:30:01,401
- The number of stations mattered. - Per station?

868
00:30:02,001 --> 00:30:03,401
So you got paid for each station.

869
00:30:03,841 --> 00:30:06,441
Was it like this? "This station is..."

870
00:30:06,541 --> 00:30:07,810
(Shin Dong is good at copying him.)

871
00:30:07,811 --> 00:30:09,641
- That was good. - You got a pass.

872
00:30:09,711 --> 00:30:10,810
- Goodness. - He gave you a pass.

873
00:30:10,811 --> 00:30:12,680
"To Men on a Mission, the door will open on your right."

874
00:30:12,681 --> 00:30:14,011
"All right!"

875
00:30:14,681 --> 00:30:17,321
(The announcement became lively.)

876
00:30:17,521 --> 00:30:18,950
(It feels like we need to dance when we get off.)

877
00:30:18,951 --> 00:30:20,251
- That sounds good. - Like someone who pushes people.

878
00:30:20,791 --> 00:30:21,890
- Someone who pushes people? - You did it.

879
00:30:21,891 --> 00:30:23,921
- You could be someone like them. - My goodness.

880
00:30:24,921 --> 00:30:27,590
I think Doh Hyeong has so many fans abroad.

881
00:30:27,591 --> 00:30:29,390
Because you worked in the games...

882
00:30:29,391 --> 00:30:30,560
- that we all know. - Of course.

883
00:30:30,561 --> 00:30:31,730
You were in animations too.

884
00:30:31,731 --> 00:30:33,830
In fact, the one that Ho Dong and Soo Geun talked about...

885
00:30:33,831 --> 00:30:36,500
"Miraculous?" The one you said this.

886
00:30:36,501 --> 00:30:37,501
- Miracle. - That's the character...

887
00:30:37,501 --> 00:30:38,501
that represents me.

888
00:30:38,502 --> 00:30:40,241
- Gosh. I apologize. - Its full name is...

889
00:30:40,441 --> 00:30:41,441
Please forget about it.

890
00:30:41,442 --> 00:30:42,540
I'm okay with it.

891
00:30:42,541 --> 00:30:44,581
But Ho Dong got it wrong though he read it.

892
00:30:45,111 --> 00:30:47,381
It's because he's from the older generation.

893
00:30:47,611 --> 00:30:50,881
The title is "Miraculous: Tales of Ladybug and Cat Noir."

894
00:30:51,121 --> 00:30:53,421
I've been on it since 2015.

895
00:30:53,621 --> 00:30:55,821
It's still being aired, and there will be more seasons.

896
00:30:56,051 --> 00:30:58,190
Back then... Now there's Japanese dubbing.

897
00:30:58,191 --> 00:30:59,560
But there was only Korean dubbing.

898
00:30:59,561 --> 00:31:00,930
- So people watched with subtitles. - There were subtitles.

899
00:31:00,931 --> 00:31:02,390
So in Japan, people watched it...

900
00:31:02,391 --> 00:31:03,830
- Of course. - with subtitles.

901
00:31:03,831 --> 00:31:07,470
And there were many comments saying they liked my voice.

902
00:31:07,471 --> 00:31:10,371
There was an event of the show in Korea once.

903
00:31:10,541 --> 00:31:12,171
A Japanese fan came to me.

904
00:31:12,571 --> 00:31:14,911
- From Japan? - He said he came to see me.

905
00:31:15,411 --> 00:31:16,411
- Mr. Doh Hyeong. - He was here that day...

906
00:31:16,411 --> 00:31:17,411
and was going back that night.

907
00:31:18,241 --> 00:31:19,811
He asked me to visit Japan too.

908
00:31:20,111 --> 00:31:23,580
Actually, I had to visit Tokyo two months later.

909
00:31:23,581 --> 00:31:25,851
On my way to the Haneda Airport, I wrote on my SNS,

910
00:31:26,021 --> 00:31:28,491
"I'd like to meet my fans from Japan."

911
00:31:28,751 --> 00:31:32,461
"If you want to see me, please come." I posted this.

912
00:31:32,921 --> 00:31:36,161
So when I arrived at the airport, and when the gate opened,

913
00:31:36,861 --> 00:31:39,200
- Fans were there? - I heard people screaming.

914
00:31:39,201 --> 00:31:40,770
- My goodness. - You were like Bae Yong Joon.

915
00:31:40,771 --> 00:31:42,300
I was surprised, and when I looked up,

916
00:31:42,301 --> 00:31:45,871
there were 40 to 50 Japanese fans with signs.

917
00:31:46,671 --> 00:31:49,070
- My goodness. - At first, only my fans gathered.

918
00:31:49,071 --> 00:31:51,781
But everyone gathered because they thought I was a Korean star.

919
00:31:52,111 --> 00:31:54,551
- That must've been amazing. - The airport was packed.

920
00:31:55,011 --> 00:31:57,980
The security officers and guards came...

921
00:31:57,981 --> 00:31:59,650
and led us out.

922
00:31:59,651 --> 00:32:02,920
After that, I had two official fan meetings in Japan.

923
00:32:02,921 --> 00:32:05,420
I had two fan meetings at Ikebukuro.

924
00:32:05,421 --> 00:32:07,790
- In Japan, voice actors... - That's right.

925
00:32:07,791 --> 00:32:09,130
- They have a concert too. - They hold a concert.

926
00:32:09,131 --> 00:32:10,930
They hold a concert and everything.

927
00:32:10,931 --> 00:32:13,001
- This is what's really amazing. - Seriously. He's so amazing.

928
00:32:13,201 --> 00:32:15,271
I told my daughter that I would be on Men on a Mission.

929
00:32:15,401 --> 00:32:17,640
She asked me who would be on the show with me. And I told her.

930
00:32:17,641 --> 00:32:19,241
She didn't mention anyone else except him.

931
00:32:20,141 --> 00:32:22,771
She said, "Nam Doh Hyeong?"

932
00:32:23,681 --> 00:32:27,081
She says he's the most popular voice actor these days.

933
00:32:27,411 --> 00:32:28,650
Among young people in their teens and 20s.

934
00:32:28,651 --> 00:32:31,880
Seriously. Even when her parents are both voice actors.

935
00:32:31,881 --> 00:32:33,850
- She says he's the most popular. - And all of their friends too.

936
00:32:33,851 --> 00:32:36,550
- Thank you, Ye In. - Doh Hyeong is...

937
00:32:36,551 --> 00:32:38,860
the top voice actor in Korea.

938
00:32:38,861 --> 00:32:41,930
He also has many fans in Japan.

939
00:32:41,931 --> 00:32:44,000
And it's not only Japan. He's famous in Europe too.

940
00:32:44,001 --> 00:32:46,030
- Even in Europe. - He's the most popular voice actor.

941
00:32:46,031 --> 00:32:48,200
- He's very hot these days. - It's because Ji Hwan, Sun,

942
00:32:48,201 --> 00:32:49,830
and Soo Jin paved the way for me.

943
00:32:49,831 --> 00:32:51,140
- I really feel thankful for them. - Me?

944
00:32:51,141 --> 00:32:52,400
- Where did I do that? - That's enough now.

945
00:32:52,401 --> 00:32:53,640
- I really mean it. - But...

946
00:32:53,641 --> 00:32:55,741
"Where did I do that?"

947
00:32:55,841 --> 00:32:58,610
I also hold fan meetings every year on my birthday.

948
00:32:58,611 --> 00:33:01,411
There were 500 fans the year before last, and 400 to 500 fans last year.

949
00:33:01,511 --> 00:33:03,950
This year, there will be 400 fans. It will be next week.

950
00:33:03,951 --> 00:33:06,221
Tickets were sold out in 30 seconds in all of them.

951
00:33:06,991 --> 00:33:08,490
(Nam Doh Hyeong is really popular these days.)

952
00:33:08,491 --> 00:33:10,890
- They all paved the way for me. - This is what I heard about him.

953
00:33:10,891 --> 00:33:13,831
Apparently, Doh Hyeong is really good at this.

954
00:33:14,091 --> 00:33:17,001
- What is it? - He's really great in death scenes.

955
00:33:17,131 --> 00:33:18,231
- Is that his specialty? - Right.

956
00:33:18,331 --> 00:33:20,130
- He's good at acting a death scene. - That's his specialty?

957
00:33:20,131 --> 00:33:23,501
In animations, characters die with one last cry.

958
00:33:23,601 --> 00:33:25,800
- But I dub a lot of games too. - Right.

959
00:33:25,801 --> 00:33:30,010
In games, various death sounds come out at the touch of a button.

960
00:33:30,011 --> 00:33:31,580
There's a long death and a short death.

961
00:33:31,581 --> 00:33:33,211
There's also a case where a character dies in two parts.

962
00:33:33,481 --> 00:33:34,610
- In two parts? - How do you do that?

963
00:33:34,611 --> 00:33:36,151
- I do it like a vending machine. - Right.

964
00:33:36,381 --> 00:33:38,080
For example, this is a long death sound.

965
00:33:38,081 --> 00:33:40,650
(A long death sound)

966
00:33:40,651 --> 00:33:42,250
I think I've heard this before.

967
00:33:42,251 --> 00:33:43,420
- I think I've heard this. - Gosh. It sounds painful.

968
00:33:43,421 --> 00:33:44,890
It's when a character falls into a well.

969
00:33:44,891 --> 00:33:47,661
And then they give me a request to die a bit shorter than that.

970
00:33:49,061 --> 00:33:51,130
This time, the character is stabbed to death.

971
00:33:51,131 --> 00:33:52,500
So they ask me to groan inwardly.

972
00:33:52,501 --> 00:33:55,571
(The sound that a character is stabbed to death)

973
00:33:56,031 --> 00:33:57,141
- And... - My goodness.

974
00:33:57,341 --> 00:33:58,601
- That's good. - So funny.

975
00:33:59,271 --> 00:34:01,741
When you first become a professional voice actor,

976
00:34:01,941 --> 00:34:03,271
you always have to do death scenes.

977
00:34:03,481 --> 00:34:05,310
- You have to do Soldiers 1 to 27... - Right.

978
00:34:05,311 --> 00:34:07,580
by yourself, and most of them die.

979
00:34:07,581 --> 00:34:09,580
Which one is the most memorable death you dubbed?

980
00:34:09,581 --> 00:34:11,351
The one where I died by a flame thrower.

981
00:34:11,481 --> 00:34:13,121
- By a flame thrower? - How do you express that?

982
00:34:13,421 --> 00:34:15,251
(Screaming)

983
00:34:16,791 --> 00:34:20,560
(He acts passionately using his whole body.)

984
00:34:20,561 --> 00:34:22,230
- I did it like this. - You must've made a fuss.

985
00:34:22,231 --> 00:34:23,700
- Yes, I made a fuss. - That's so sad.

986
00:34:23,701 --> 00:34:26,630
But the director said, "I can't hear the lead's lines."

987
00:34:26,631 --> 00:34:27,731
"Die again."

988
00:34:28,501 --> 00:34:30,470
So I did it again. I did dying by a flame thrower again.

989
00:34:30,471 --> 00:34:32,101
So you can't be too loud.

990
00:34:32,201 --> 00:34:33,810
I guess it was when you dubbed together.

991
00:34:33,811 --> 00:34:36,471
While I'm screaming because of the flame thrower,

992
00:34:36,711 --> 00:34:38,210
the enemy tries to shoot me.

993
00:34:38,211 --> 00:34:39,541
But then, someone stops him.

994
00:34:39,611 --> 00:34:41,180
"Leave him." Then...

995
00:34:41,181 --> 00:34:43,550
I have to scream until I die.

996
00:34:43,551 --> 00:34:44,950
- Because of a flame thrower. - We do that for so long.

997
00:34:44,951 --> 00:34:47,650
The easiest one is dying by a sniper.

998
00:34:47,651 --> 00:34:49,751
- How do you do that? - Because you die right away.

999
00:34:49,891 --> 00:34:50,990
Without a sound.

1000
