1498
00:51:33,391 --> 00:51:34,391
Right.

1499
00:51:34,392 --> 00:51:36,930
You should have at least said, "It's a baby!"

1500
00:51:36,931 --> 00:51:37,931
Right.

1501
00:51:38,501 --> 00:51:41,030
You should have made your presence known.

1502
00:51:41,031 --> 00:51:42,530
- You should have said something. - But it was a great drama...

1503
00:51:42,531 --> 00:51:46,170
I really wanted to be accepted as a cast.

1504
00:51:46,171 --> 00:51:48,840
And I got accepted...

1505
00:51:48,841 --> 00:51:50,410
even though it was a minor role.

1506
00:51:50,411 --> 00:51:51,940
- Congratulations. - You two were both there.

1507
00:51:51,941 --> 00:51:53,940
I'm really happy the drama became successful.

1508
00:51:53,941 --> 00:51:55,310
Let's meet at the after-party.

1509
00:51:55,311 --> 00:51:56,311
Okay.

1510
00:51:56,581 --> 00:51:59,450
We have the last part now.

1511
00:51:59,451 --> 00:52:00,820
On the last part,

1512
00:52:00,821 --> 00:52:02,790
you wrote "Dubbing the best scenes of Men on a Mission."

1513
00:52:02,791 --> 00:52:03,920
The best scenes of Men on a Mission?

1514
00:52:03,921 --> 00:52:05,790
The best scenes of Men on a Mission?

1515
00:52:05,791 --> 00:52:08,160
- You will dub? - You will dub the scenes?

1516
00:52:08,161 --> 00:52:10,030
- Men on a Mission? - Our show.

1517
00:52:10,031 --> 00:52:11,901
Is there anything to dub on our show?

1518
00:52:12,531 --> 00:52:13,560
- It's too... - Then...

1519
00:52:13,561 --> 00:52:14,571
"Welcome to the McDonald's."

1520
00:52:14,831 --> 00:52:17,701
(Something Happened in Saipan)

1521
00:52:18,041 --> 00:52:21,640
(In Episode 441, they played a game for a feast.)

1522
00:52:21,641 --> 00:52:22,871
- Have you no wits? - It was too much.

1523
00:52:23,141 --> 00:52:26,411
(We would've won had you gotten "Guinness World Records.")

1524
00:52:26,511 --> 00:52:29,411
(I got "Update" and a few more.)

1525
00:52:29,911 --> 00:52:33,451
(You've talked about "Guinness World Records" for hours.)

1526
00:52:34,451 --> 00:52:38,620
(When Yeong Cheol scolds Ho Dong continuously,)

1527
00:52:38,621 --> 00:52:43,361
(Ho Dong becomes annoyed.)

1528
00:52:44,961 --> 00:52:50,371
(Yeong Cheol becomes wary and comforts Ho Dong belatedly.)

1529
00:52:51,001 --> 00:52:54,171
(We won three consecutive times. Let's keep it fun.)

1530
00:52:54,441 --> 00:52:58,311
(How will the voice actors change the scene?)

1531
00:52:58,781 --> 00:53:00,140
- We'll give it a go. - Okay.

1532
00:53:00,141 --> 00:53:01,141
(The legendary voice actors dub Men on a Mission.)

1533
00:53:01,311 --> 00:53:03,211
Will you turn off the audio?

1534
00:53:03,611 --> 00:53:05,080
- They should do that. - They'll turn it off.

1535
00:53:05,081 --> 00:53:06,381
- Okay. - How will they time it?

1536
00:53:06,581 --> 00:53:08,591
We just need to know the starting point.

1537
00:53:09,351 --> 00:53:12,091
(Something Happened in Saipan, dubbed version)

1538
00:53:12,661 --> 00:53:17,031
For goodness' sake. I really can't believe you.

1539
00:53:17,291 --> 00:53:21,701
For goodness' sake. I really can't believe you.

1540
00:53:21,801 --> 00:53:24,001
I got "Update" and a few more.

1541
00:53:24,231 --> 00:53:26,840
You've talked about "Guinness World Records" for hours.

1542
00:53:26,841 --> 00:53:28,540
Please don't misunderstand.

1543
00:53:28,541 --> 00:53:31,141
- They're filming a video. - Did you do such a great job?

1544
00:53:31,711 --> 00:53:34,651
It was an important moment.

1545
00:53:34,781 --> 00:53:36,410
I know that it was. I'm sorry.

1546
00:53:36,411 --> 00:53:38,821
Right. If we were going to lose, we would've lost the 1st 2 rounds.

1547
00:53:39,351 --> 00:53:40,450
Still, we did well.

1548
00:53:40,451 --> 00:53:42,020
We had three consecutive wins.

1549
00:53:42,021 --> 00:53:43,850
Let's enjoy the game. Didn't we come to Saipan to laugh?

1550
00:53:43,851 --> 00:53:46,421
You have the skills, but you don't make an effort.

1551
00:53:47,691 --> 00:53:52,201
(Ho Dong becomes very cute.)

1552
00:53:52,331 --> 00:53:56,531
- Ho Dong seems so intimidated. - Seriously.

1553
00:53:57,031 --> 00:53:59,670
- It's fun. - Ho Dong's tone is so funny.

1554
00:53:59,671 --> 00:54:02,971
- They made it funny. - The voice changes the concept.

1555
00:54:03,071 --> 00:54:04,211
Well done.

1556
00:54:04,641 --> 00:54:05,911
Well done, everyone.

1557
00:54:06,130 --> 00:54:07,610
After the long winter,

1558
00:54:07,611 --> 00:54:10,680
people welcomed spring eagerly. But summer came so suddenly.

1559
00:54:10,681 --> 00:54:12,421
How hot will it get in summer?

1560
00:54:12,551 --> 00:54:14,691
Let's delve into the heat wave!

1561
00:54:14,791 --> 00:54:17,091
Spring, I'm sorry.

1562
00:54:17,751 --> 00:54:19,821
Forgive me for being unable to save you.

1563
00:54:20,521 --> 00:54:23,991
I'll leave behind a blanket for you.

1564
00:54:24,431 --> 00:54:26,201
You know what?

1565
00:54:26,361 --> 00:54:29,471
Challenging yourself makes your life the coolest!

1566
00:54:29,671 --> 00:54:33,771
Excessive worrying only hurts the body and mind.

1567
00:54:34,441 --> 00:54:36,510
Now, we'll recruit the voice actors of the Brother School...

1568
00:54:36,511 --> 00:54:38,811
who'll fight against the heat wave this summer.

1569
00:54:39,441 --> 00:54:41,310
Who'll be the sole survivor...

1570
00:54:41,311 --> 00:54:43,681
of the cutthroat voice-acting war?

1571
00:54:44,281 --> 00:54:47,450
Vocal Class Wars: Voice Actors on a Mission.

1572
00:54:47,451 --> 00:54:49,490
(Vocal Class Wars: Voice Actors on a Mission)

1573
00:54:49,491 --> 00:54:50,621
Cut!

1574
00:54:51,221 --> 00:54:53,020
It was great. You guys don't disappoint.

1575
00:54:53,021 --> 00:54:55,690
The ace members of the Radio Club did so well.

1576
00:54:55,691 --> 00:54:57,031
You guys must be hot. Come on out.

1577
00:54:57,161 --> 00:54:59,001
Come on out.

1578
00:54:59,331 --> 00:55:02,001
Please take a seat. All right.

1579
00:55:02,301 --> 00:55:04,400
- You guys did so well. - Was it okay? Should we try again?

1580
00:55:04,401 --> 00:55:05,540
- Was it okay? - It won't be necessary.

1581
00:55:05,541 --> 00:55:06,900
- Was it okay? - "Let's delve into it" was great.

1582
00:55:06,901 --> 00:55:08,370
- "Let's delve into it." - I see.

1583
00:55:08,371 --> 00:55:09,510
- Was it okay? - Yes.

1584
00:55:09,511 --> 00:55:12,380
I heard that the final interview was taking place today.

1585
00:55:12,381 --> 00:55:14,110
- How many people are coming? - How many are we picking?

1586
00:55:14,111 --> 00:55:15,910
I hope they'll be some useful ones.

1587
00:55:15,911 --> 00:55:18,280
Don't get me started. So many people applied.

1588
00:55:18,281 --> 00:55:20,680
Through vigorous screening, I narrowed them down...

1589
00:55:20,681 --> 00:55:23,091
- to seven applicants. - Seven?

1590
00:55:23,291 --> 00:55:25,521
Watch them carefully...

1591
00:55:25,891 --> 00:55:27,420
- and have a pick. - Okay.

1592
00:55:27,421 --> 00:55:28,790
They should be here soon.

1593
00:55:28,791 --> 00:55:30,930
Are you ready? Please come on in.

1594
00:55:30,931 --> 00:55:32,500
Are the interviewees here?

1595
00:55:32,501 --> 00:55:33,631
- They're here. - Hello.

1596
00:55:33,861 --> 00:55:37,131
- Hello. - They're the juniors.

1597
00:55:38,201 --> 00:55:42,041
- All right. - A, E, I, O, U.

1598
00:55:42,341 --> 00:55:44,471
(An aspiring voice actor who has a big mouth and body)

1599
00:55:44,781 --> 00:55:45,781
(An aspiring classical singer who came to the wrong club)

1600
00:55:45,782 --> 00:55:48,110
All right. Please take a seat.

1601
00:55:48,111 --> 00:55:49,751
Please take a seat.

1602
00:55:50,151 --> 00:55:53,550
All right. This summer, that man will make a comeback.

1603
00:55:53,551 --> 00:55:54,651
Yes.

1604
00:55:55,121 --> 00:55:56,191
Yes.

1605
00:55:56,491 --> 00:55:57,890
Welcome to the final interview...

1606
00:55:57,891 --> 00:56:00,960
for recruiting the new voice actors of the Radio Club.

1607
00:56:00,961 --> 00:56:01,961
(Everyone, welcome.)

1608
00:56:01,962 --> 00:56:03,890
- Seniors, we love you. - Seniors.

1609
00:56:03,891 --> 00:56:06,360
- Thank you. - I can't believe it.

1610
00:56:06,361 --> 00:56:09,230
- I really enjoyed "One Piece." - Kang Soo Jin.

1611
00:56:09,231 --> 00:56:10,730
You're my dream.

1612
00:56:10,731 --> 00:56:11,741
(Soo Jin is my dream.)

1613
00:56:11,871 --> 00:56:13,140
Before we begin the test in earnest,

1614
00:56:13,141 --> 00:56:14,940
- I have a question. - Okay.

1615
00:56:14,941 --> 00:56:17,771
Do any characters make you think, "I really suit this character?"

1616
00:56:18,241 --> 00:56:21,041
"I was born for this character."

1617
00:56:21,211 --> 00:56:23,580
As for me, I want to play the king.

1618
00:56:23,581 --> 00:56:24,711
- The king. - The king.

1619
00:56:24,781 --> 00:56:26,750
I'm very much interested in period dramas.

1620
00:56:26,751 --> 00:56:30,151
- I see. - I think I'll do well in them.

1621
00:56:31,421 --> 00:56:33,821
However!

1622
00:56:34,091 --> 00:56:35,360
- What? - However!

1623
00:56:35,361 --> 00:56:36,530
- What was that? - However!

1624
00:56:36,531 --> 00:56:37,760
- However. - However.

1625
00:56:37,761 --> 00:56:38,830
"However?"

1626
00:56:38,831 --> 00:56:40,600
(Even Wang Geon would weep...)

1627
00:56:40,601 --> 00:56:43,231
(upon hearing the loud voice of a 2-m man.)

1628
00:56:43,531 --> 00:56:45,700
- Try, "Do I have a king's face?" - Is there anything unique?

1629
00:56:45,701 --> 00:56:48,470
"Do I have a king's face?"

1630
00:56:48,471 --> 00:56:49,541
He has a nice voice.

1631
00:56:49,711 --> 00:56:51,140
I think he'll be the king despite looking like a bandit.

1632
00:56:51,141 --> 00:56:52,580
It's like he's doing an impression of a celebrity.

1633
00:56:52,581 --> 00:56:56,481
(The king of the bandits)

1634
00:56:56,581 --> 00:56:58,150
Does anyone have experience...

1635
00:56:58,151 --> 00:57:01,650
- in dubbing or narrating? - I bet many people do.

1636
00:57:01,651 --> 00:57:02,850
I have an experience.

1637
00:57:02,851 --> 00:57:05,120
As for me, I narrated a documentary.

1638
00:57:05,121 --> 00:57:06,760
- A documentary? - "Our Oceans."

1639
00:57:06,761 --> 00:57:08,430
It's difficult to narrate a documentary.

1640
00:57:08,431 --> 00:57:09,990
Barack Obama did the English version...

1641
00:57:09,991 --> 00:57:12,230
and I did the Korean version.

1642
00:57:12,231 --> 00:57:14,231
- Say a line from the documentary. - Go ahead.

1643
00:57:14,731 --> 00:57:16,871
- I bet he forgot. - Three, two, one.

1644
00:57:18,031 --> 00:57:19,141
"Our oceans."

1645
00:57:21,171 --> 00:57:23,571
"In the Pacific Ocean,"

1646
00:57:23,741 --> 00:57:25,580
"a dolphin swims."

1647
00:57:25,581 --> 00:57:26,581
(He fails to swim.)

1648
00:57:26,582 --> 00:57:27,710
What was that?

1649
00:57:27,711 --> 00:57:29,511
Let me make some more preparations.

1650
00:57:30,111 --> 00:57:31,680
"Our oceans." The first line...

1651
00:57:31,681 --> 00:57:33,250
- was stable. - He's good.

1652
00:57:33,251 --> 00:57:34,920
It's embarrassing,

1653
00:57:34,921 --> 00:57:36,991
but Senior Dong and I dubbed a movie.

1654
00:57:37,421 --> 00:57:39,090
- "Alvin and the Chipmunks." - "Alvin and the Chipmunks."

1655
00:57:39,091 --> 00:57:42,390
I played Simon among the chipmunk trio.

1656
00:57:42,391 --> 00:57:45,730
Back then, Ji Hwan and I hosted...

1657
00:57:45,731 --> 00:57:46,860
"Inkigayo."

1658
00:57:46,861 --> 00:57:48,801
So I received advice from him.

1659
00:57:48,931 --> 00:57:49,931
It was so hard.

1660
00:57:49,932 --> 00:57:51,601
I had to speak quite fast.

1661
00:57:51,701 --> 00:57:54,040
"Alvin, where are you going?"

1662
00:57:54,041 --> 00:57:56,510
- Then they sped up the lines. - It suits you.

1663
00:57:56,511 --> 00:57:57,570
That's right.

1664
00:57:57,571 --> 00:57:59,041
It's substandard.

1665
00:57:59,341 --> 00:58:01,850
The movie received a lot of love from children.

1666
00:58:01,851 --> 00:58:04,180
- He learned well. - As you know,

1667
00:58:04,181 --> 00:58:05,481
I dubbed "Shrek."

1668
00:58:06,081 --> 00:58:10,120
- I played the worst villain, - Did you dub "Shrek?"

1669
00:58:10,121 --> 00:58:11,720
Rumpelstiltskin.

1670
00:58:11,721 --> 00:58:14,220
"I'll end Shrek, that jerk."

1671
00:58:14,221 --> 00:58:15,991
"I'll catch him."

1672
00:58:16,261 --> 00:58:17,391
Grandpa.

1673
00:58:17,691 --> 00:58:18,861
"Don't go."

1674
00:58:19,731 --> 00:58:21,870
- Grandpa. - "I'm telling you."

1675
00:58:21,871 --> 00:58:22,971
- Listen. - Yes?

1676
00:58:23,401 --> 00:58:25,241
- They can change their voices. - Yes.

1677
00:58:25,441 --> 00:58:26,970
- You know, - They have talent.

1678
00:58:26,971 --> 00:58:28,940
- they have a lot of experience. - Yes.

1679
00:58:28,941 --> 00:58:32,681
However, we'll choose only one person...

1680
00:58:32,911 --> 00:58:34,981
through some tests.

1681
00:58:35,081 --> 00:58:38,720
So don't be so proud. We'll now begin the first test...

1682
00:58:38,721 --> 00:58:41,081
that checks your unique voice and acting skills,

1683
00:58:41,221 --> 00:58:43,850
the essentials of a voice actor.

1684
00:58:43,851 --> 00:58:46,291
- All right. - Do you get tested like this?

1685
00:58:46,361 --> 00:58:47,720
- Does it go like this? - It goes like this.

1686
00:58:47,721 --> 00:58:50,260
- There's a window. - What's this?

1687
00:58:50,261 --> 00:58:53,861
The first test is the Script Test.

1688
00:58:54,031 --> 00:58:56,600
Voice actors take a variety of works such as movies,

1689
00:58:56,601 --> 00:58:59,070
animated series, documentaries, games, and commercials.

1690
00:58:59,071 --> 00:59:01,640
We'll see how well you can pull off...

1691
00:59:01,641 --> 00:59:03,841
these lines...

1692
00:59:03,971 --> 00:59:05,581
in your own style.

1693
00:59:05,981 --> 00:59:07,840
- Who will go first? - Whoever wants to go first.

1694
00:59:07,841 --> 00:59:09,610
- I'll begin. - Kyung Hoon will begin.

1695
00:59:09,611 --> 00:59:10,850
- Kyung Hoon will go right away. - Okay.

1696
00:59:10,851 --> 00:59:12,450
Seniors, please take a look.

1697
00:59:12,451 --> 00:59:14,950
I'll take number two and deliver...

1698
00:59:14,951 --> 00:59:16,051
- an old man's lines. - Okay.

1699
00:59:16,151 --> 00:59:17,991
- He'll play an old man. - Yes.

1700
00:59:18,191 --> 00:59:19,491
- It's long. - Get ready.

1701
00:59:20,321 --> 00:59:21,391
Action.

1702
00:59:21,621 --> 00:59:23,461
"Try them on."

1703
00:59:23,861 --> 00:59:27,431
"The restaurant owner gave me these for the price of fried chicken."

1704
00:59:28,731 --> 00:59:30,100
"If you wear them,"

1705
00:59:30,101 --> 00:59:32,841
"my heart will become lighter."

1706
00:59:33,141 --> 00:59:34,941
"Try them on and see if they fit."

1707
00:59:35,511 --> 00:59:36,571
"They fit, right?"

1708
00:59:36,911 --> 00:59:39,541
"I saw people's feet all my life,"

1709
00:59:39,641 --> 00:59:42,381
"so I can get the right size in a single glance."

1710
00:59:43,951 --> 00:59:46,621
"Perhaps you don't like the shape."

1711
00:59:46,981 --> 00:59:50,151
"All right. Wear them well. That's all I want."

1712
00:59:50,351 --> 00:59:51,891
"That's all I want."

1713
00:59:55,291 --> 00:59:57,530
(Kyung Hoon's acting was neat.)

1714
00:59:57,531 --> 00:59:59,261
- He did well. - What did you think?

1715
00:59:59,361 --> 01:00:02,000
When you play an old person, you need to think about...

1716
01:00:02,001 --> 01:00:04,400
your posture and age.

1717
01:00:04,401 --> 01:00:07,240
What's the situation? Are you on the street...

1718
01:00:07,241 --> 01:00:09,510
or in the house?

1719
01:00:09,511 --> 01:00:12,480
Depending on the setting, your tone and volume need to change.

1720
01:00:12,481 --> 01:00:14,781
But there were no such settings whatsoever.

1721
01:00:14,841 --> 01:00:16,450
- It was a bit... - He failed.

1722
01:00:16,451 --> 01:00:18,680
I think you'll do a better job of playing a child,

1723
01:00:18,681 --> 01:00:20,420
- not an old person. - Okay.

1724
01:00:20,421 --> 01:00:22,250
A child, not an old person.

1725
01:00:22,251 --> 01:00:23,321
(Another old man appears.)

1726
01:00:24,391 --> 01:00:26,121
"Try them on."

1727
01:00:26,821 --> 01:00:30,260
"The restaurant owner gave me these for the price of fried chicken."

1728
01:00:30,261 --> 01:00:31,390
(Giggling)

1729
01:00:31,391 --> 01:00:32,400
You're like...

1730
01:00:32,401 --> 01:00:35,500
"The restaurant owner gave me these for the price of fried chicken."

1731
01:00:35,501 --> 01:00:38,641
(The genre went from humanism to thriller.)

1732
01:00:38,801 --> 01:00:40,740
You're like a character in "Korean Ghost Stories."

1733
01:00:40,741 --> 01:00:43,071
"I saw people's feet all my life,"

1734
01:00:43,171 --> 01:00:45,541
"so I can get the right size in a single glance."

1735
01:00:45,841 --> 01:00:48,510
(I know your shoe size as well.)

1736
01:00:48,511 --> 01:00:52,450
I watched this drama, "The Good Detective."

1737
01:00:52,451 --> 01:00:55,090
Park Geun Hyung doesn't act like that.

1738
01:00:55,091 --> 01:00:56,790
What do you know, you punk?

1739
01:00:56,791 --> 01:00:58,991
(Sir?)

1740
01:00:59,161 --> 01:01:00,460
- Hey. - You...

1741
01:01:00,461 --> 01:01:01,890
Don't say "Hey" to an old man!

1742
01:01:01,891 --> 01:01:04,131
(He's a scary grandpa.)

1743
01:01:04,431 --> 01:01:06,430
As for Soo Geun...

1744
01:01:06,431 --> 01:01:08,730
When you play an old man,

1745
01:01:08,731 --> 01:01:11,031
you need to show the aged body.

1746
01:01:11,231 --> 01:01:14,500
Soo Geun showed the aged body right away,

1747
01:01:14,501 --> 01:01:17,240
so the beginning was good.

1748
01:01:17,241 --> 01:01:19,280
